      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm working on an embedded c++ project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow memory leak. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually runs out of available ram and crashes. i don't see any obvious missing deletes in my main loop. how should i go about systematically finding where the leak is happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To find the memory leak in your embedded C++ project, you can start by using a memory profiling tool designed for embedded systems, such as Valgrind's Memcheck or the Electric Fence. These tools can help you identify where memory is being allocated but not properly freed. \n\nAs you go through the code, keep an eye out for any dynamic memory allocations, such as `new` or `malloc`, and make sure they're paired with corresponding `delete` or `free` statements. If you find any, double-check that they're being called at the right time and that they're not being called multiple times for the same memory block.\n\nIn addition, you can also use a debugger to step through your code and watch for any memory allocations that aren't being freed. If you find any, make sure to fix them and then run your tests again to see if the leak still exists.\n\nRemember, memory leaks can be sneaky and hard to find, so it's important to be thorough and patient when searching for them. Good luck!",
      "source": "target",
